\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} x  of reflexivity data to each vertex.

Let f , g \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}Bx be two dependent functions. A homotopy from f to g, writing H\colon  f \sim  g is given by a dependent function H\colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}fx=gx. We shall write 1_{f}\colon  f \sim  f for the identity homotopy on f defined by 1_{f}x:\equiv  \mathsf {refl}.

A reflexive graph \mathcal {A} is called univalent when for all x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 the type \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y is a proposition, or (equivalently), is contractible with centre 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We shall refer to a univalent reflexive graph as a path object.
